"""
MKT Context Commentary — Ezekiel chapters 33–35
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-ezekiel-33-35.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/ezekiel.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/ezekiel.json (MKT text)
- data/translation/glossary-hebrew.json (contested terms)

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch 33 marks the structural turning point of Ezekiel: the fall of Jerusalem
  (v. 21) ends Ezekiel's muteness and shifts the book from judgment to restoration.
- The watchman re-commission (33:1-9) recapitulates 3:17-21 — contextually
  significant as Ezekiel reassumes his prophetic role after the city's fall.
- Ch 34's shepherd oracle is one of the most theologically important in Ezekiel:
  YHWH himself becomes the shepherd over against failed human shepherds (kings).
- Ch 35 (oracle against Mount Seir/Edom) is contextually placed to contrast with
  the restoration of Israel's mountains in ch. 36; Edom's desolation = Israel's
  restoration are the two sides of the same divine act.
- Throughout: 'shepherds' = rulers/kings in ANE convention; the David-to-come
  (34:23-24) is the Messianic king who will fulfil what Judah's kings failed to do.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EZEKIEL = {
  "33": {
    "1": "<p>The oracular introduction &ldquo;the word of the LORD came to me&rdquo; opens a major structural unit in Ezekiel: chapters 33&ndash;48 constitute the book&rsquo;s restoration section. Chapter 33 is the hinge: it recapitulates the watchman commission (3:17-21) and records the fall of Jerusalem (v. 21), after which Ezekiel&rsquo;s ministry shifts definitively from judgment to restoration. The repetition of the watchman oracle at this juncture is not accidental &mdash; the fall of Jerusalem validates all the judgment oracles and now resets the prophetic mission on new terms.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The watchman parable uses the civic institution of the sentinel posted on city walls to warn of approaching military threat. The term <em>tzofeh</em> (watchman, sentinel) appears in Isa 21:6-12 and Hab 2:1 for the prophet&rsquo;s role; here its social function in Near Eastern walled cities provides the parable&rsquo;s frame. Walled cities of the ancient Levant routinely posted watchmen on towers or city gates whose primary function was early warning of raiding parties or advancing armies. The community&rsquo;s safety depended on the watchman sounding the alarm in time.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The trumpet (<em>shofar</em>) was the standard military alarm instrument in ancient Israel (Num 10:9; Judg 3:27; 1 Sam 13:3). Its distinctive blast was designed to cut through ambient noise and reach the entire population. The parable&rsquo;s mechanics are legally precise: the watchman&rsquo;s obligation is to sound the alarm when he perceives the danger. Whether the hearer responds is not within the watchman&rsquo;s control &mdash; responsibility shifts to the hearer who has received warning.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The legal principle of transferred blood-guilt: if the alarm is sounded and the person ignores it, &ldquo;his blood is on his own head.&rdquo; This is the Israelite legal formula of self-incurred blood-guilt, used in Lev 20:9-16; Josh 2:19; 2 Sam 1:16. The watchman&rsquo;s action has fulfilled the moral-legal obligation; the hearer&rsquo;s inaction makes the hearer responsible for their own fate. The casuistic legal form (&ldquo;if... then&rdquo;) is characteristic of Levitical and prophetic legal discourse.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The double principle: the hearer who ignores warning dies in self-incurred guilt; the hearer who heeds the warning saves (<em>mallat</em>) their own life. The word <em>mallat</em> (to escape, to deliver oneself) is used in legal and narrative contexts for survival of mortal threat. In the prophetic application, &ldquo;saving one&rsquo;s life&rdquo; means responding to YHWH&rsquo;s warning through repentance &mdash; the moral-spiritual equivalent of fleeing a besieged city.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The watchman&rsquo;s corresponding failure: if the watchman sees the sword coming and fails to sound the alarm, the community&rsquo;s blood falls on the watchman&rsquo;s head. The phrase &ldquo;taken in their own iniquity&rdquo; acknowledges that the individuals who die may indeed be guilty &mdash; but that does not excuse the watchman&rsquo;s negligence. The watchman&rsquo;s culpability is distinct from and supplementary to the community&rsquo;s guilt. The double accountability (community for their own sin; watchman for failing his duty) is the parable&rsquo;s full legal picture.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The application of the watchman parable to Ezekiel himself repeats the inaugural commission of 3:17: &ldquo;I have made you a watchman for the house of Israel.&rdquo; The repetition at this structural turning point signals a recommissioning after the fall of Jerusalem: the prophetic office continues, now directed toward the exilic community rather than toward the doomed city. The phrase &ldquo;when you hear a word from my mouth, you will warn them on my behalf&rdquo; (<em>mi-pi</em>, from my mouth) emphasizes that the watchman&rsquo;s message is received before it is transmitted &mdash; the prophet is always the conduit, never the originator.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The watchman&rsquo;s liability is spelled out: if YHWH declares a wicked person&rsquo;s death-verdict and the prophet fails to warn him, the wicked person dies in his iniquity but &ldquo;his blood I will require from your hand.&rdquo; The formula &ldquo;require from your hand&rdquo; (<em>mi-yadecha adreshenu</em>) is the legal language of blood-avenger demand &mdash; YHWH himself becomes the plaintiff claiming the blood owed by the negligent watchman. This makes prophetic silence a form of murder by omission in the covenantal order.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The converse: if the watchman warns the wicked and the wicked refuses to turn, the wicked person dies in their iniquity but the watchman &ldquo;has saved his life (<em>nefesh</em>).&rdquo; The reflexive form &ldquo;saved your life&rdquo; indicates that prophetic faithfulness is simultaneously other-directed (warning) and self-protective (releasing oneself from blood-guilt). The prophetic office is not merely vocational but morally consequential for the prophet himself &mdash; fidelity and infidelity have different outcomes not only for the audience but for the watchman.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The community&rsquo;s despairing question in exile: &ldquo;Our transgressions and our sins are upon us; we are wasting away (<em>nemoqqim</em>) because of them &mdash; how then can we live?&rdquo; The verb <em>nemoqqim</em> (to rot, to decay, to waste away) is used in Lev 26:39 for the covenant curse of exile: the people will &ldquo;rot away in their iniquity&rdquo; in the lands of their enemies. The exiles are quoting the covenant curse back at YHWH as a statement of hopelessness. The very accuracy of their diagnosis &mdash; the exile is covenant judgment &mdash; has left them unable to imagine a way forward.</p>",
    "11": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s response to the despairing exiles echoes 18:23 almost verbatim: &ldquo;As I live, I take no pleasure in the death of the wicked, but rather that the wicked turn from his way and live.&rdquo; The oath formula (<em>chai ani</em>) makes this a binding divine declaration. The imperative &ldquo;Turn back, turn back (<em>shuvu shuvu</em>) from your evil ways!&rdquo; &mdash; the doubled imperative is emphatic, even urgent. &ldquo;Why will you die, O house of Israel?&rdquo; &mdash; the rhetorical question implies that death is not the predetermined outcome; it is the unnecessary outcome of continued refusal to turn. This verse is the pivot on which all of chs. 33&ndash;48 hinge: restoration is possible.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The individual-accountability principle from ch. 18 is reiterated in abbreviated form for the post-fall context: neither past righteousness nor past wickedness is determinative in itself. The righteous person&rsquo;s righteousness will not &ldquo;deliver him&rdquo; (<em>yatzilenu</em>) on the day he transgresses. The wicked person&rsquo;s wickedness will not cause him to stumble in the day he turns from it. The governing principle is the direction of present moral orientation, not the accumulated record. This reassures the despairing exiles that past sin-accumulation does not make repentance pointless.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The case of the righteous person who trusts in their own righteousness and then sins: none of their righteous deeds will be &ldquo;remembered&rdquo; (<em>tizakarnah</em>). The verb <em>zakar</em> (to remember) in YHWH&rsquo;s judicial usage means &ldquo;to count as determinative&rdquo; &mdash; the same vocabulary as Jer 31:34 (&ldquo;I will remember their sin no more&rdquo;). To not remember the righteous deeds is to not allow them to function as a moral account balance. The warning is particularly apt for those in the exilic community who presumed on ancestral piety or personal past faithfulness to exempt themselves from accountability.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The reverse case: the wicked person who turns from sin and does what is just and right. The verbs &ldquo;turns from his sin and does&rdquo; (<em>yashuv... veasah</em>) are the standard repentance-action formula: turning (internal reorientation) plus action (external evidence). The specific acts cited in v. 15 (&ldquo;returns the pledge, repays what he has stolen, walks in the statutes of life&rdquo;) are concrete legal reparations &mdash; repentance is not merely attitudinal but involves restitution where possible.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;Returns the pledge&rdquo; (<em>chavol yashiv</em>): the debt-pledge return is specified in Exod 22:26-27 (the garment taken as collateral must be returned by nightfall). &ldquo;Repays what he has stolen&rdquo; (<em>gzelah yeshallem</em>): restitution for theft, required in Lev 6:1-5 at 100% plus 20%. &ldquo;Walks in the statutes of life without committing iniquity&rdquo;: the Torah-life as the path of <em>chayyim</em> (life), the formula from Lev 18:5 (Ezek 20:11). The repentant person does not merely cease wrongdoing but actively makes right what was done wrong &mdash; the social-restorative dimension of covenant return.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;None of the sins he has committed will be held against him&rdquo; &mdash; the definitive acquittal formula. The idiom &ldquo;held against him&rdquo; (<em>lo yizakru lo</em>) is the same memory-cancellation vocabulary as v. 13 applied in reverse. In both directions (past righteousness not shielding the apostate; past sin not condemning the repentant), the mechanism is the same: YHWH&rsquo;s judicial memory is oriented to present moral reality rather than past accounting. &ldquo;He has done what is just and right &mdash; he shall surely live.&rdquo; The doubled formula <em>chai yichyeh</em> (he shall surely live) is the emphatic verdict that concludes the righteous person&rsquo;s case.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The people&rsquo;s complaint &ldquo;the way of the Lord is not fair&rdquo; (<em>lo yittaken derek Adonai</em>) repeats almost verbatim from 18:25. The complaint&rsquo;s recurrence at ch. 33 (after the fall of Jerusalem) indicates that the population that remained in the land or was already in exile had absorbed the theological grievance without processing the earlier teaching. The refutation is identical: &ldquo;But it is their way that is not fair.&rdquo; The reversal of the charge is a rhetorical <em>ad hominem</em> &mdash; the accusation of divine inequity is itself an act of inequity by those who want divine protection without covenant faithfulness.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The two-direction principle stated succinctly: the righteous who turns to iniquity will die. The brevity of v. 18 compared to the longer case study in ch. 18 signals that Ezekiel is recapitulating a teaching already given rather than elaborating a new doctrine. The post-fall context gives the recap renewed urgency: the community that survived Jerusalem&rsquo;s fall needed the same moral clarity as the community before it fell, precisely because they might be tempted to either despair (past sin is determinative) or complacency (past righteousness provides shelter).</p>",
    "19": "<p>The inverse: the wicked who turns from wickedness and does what is just and right &ldquo;shall live because of it.&rdquo; The brevity of v. 19 matching v. 18 maintains the symmetry of the two cases. Together vv. 18-19 are a compressed restatement of the full case law of ch. 18, functioning as a reminder rather than a new disclosure. The doctrinal content (individual accountability, the moral efficacy of repentance) remains the same; what has changed is the audience&rsquo;s situation &mdash; Jerusalem has now fallen, making the call to live both more urgent and more plausible as hope.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&ldquo;Yet you say, &lsquo;The way of the Lord is not fair.&rsquo;&rdquo; The third repetition of this complaint (18:25, 18:29, and now 33:20) marks it as a fixed objection rather than a spontaneous response. YHWH&rsquo;s declaration &ldquo;I will judge each of you according to your own ways&rdquo; closes the moral accounting section and pivots to the news of Jerusalem&rsquo;s fall in v. 21. The judgment principle &mdash; individual accountability according to actual ways &mdash; is the framework within which the fall of Jerusalem is to be interpreted: not as the mechanical punishment of an innocent generation but as the consequence of the actual ways of the covenant people.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The date formula &ldquo;in the twelfth year of our exile, in the tenth month, on the fifth day of the month&rdquo; corresponds to January 8, 585 BCE (approximately), about six months after Jerusalem&rsquo;s destruction in the summer of 586 BCE (2 Kings 25:8-9: destruction in the 5th month of the 11th year). A fugitive (<em>paliyt</em>) who escaped the city&rsquo;s fall has arrived with the news: <em>hukkatah ha-ir</em> (the city has been struck down / has fallen). This moment is the structural center of the book of Ezekiel &mdash; the judgment long announced has come. From this point the oracles shift from warning to restoration.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&ldquo;The hand of the LORD had been upon me in the evening before the fugitive arrived&rdquo; &mdash; Ezekiel&rsquo;s muteness had been divinely imposed since 3:26-27 (&ldquo;I will make your tongue cling to the roof of your mouth, so that you will be mute&rdquo;) as a sign-act accompanying the judgment period. &ldquo;He had opened my mouth&rdquo; (<em>vayifatach et-pi</em>) by the time the man came: the arrival of news confirming Jerusalem&rsquo;s fall triggers the divine release of Ezekiel&rsquo;s prophetic speech capacity. &ldquo;My mouth was opened and I was silent no more&rdquo; &mdash; the restoration of speech signals the resumption of the prophetic mission in a new key: restoration rather than judgment will now dominate.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The oracular formula introduces a new divine word addressed to a different audience: those who remain in the &ldquo;ruins&rdquo; (<em>choravot</em>) of the land of Israel. Three groups survived or avoided the deportation of 586 BCE: (1) the poor left in the land by Nebuchadnezzar as vinedressers (2 Kings 25:12); (2) those who fled to Egypt taking Jeremiah with them (Jer 43-44); (3) various remnant groups in the surrounding regions. The oracle addresses those who had stayed in the ruined land and were making theological claims about it.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The remnant&rsquo;s theological argument: &ldquo;Abraham was one man, yet he possessed the land; but we are many &mdash; the land is surely given to us as our possession.&rdquo; The argument uses the Abrahamic precedent numerically: if Abraham alone, as a single man (<em>echad</em>), received the land, then the many survivors have even more claim. The argument conflates YHWH&rsquo;s promise to Abraham with an unconditional entitlement for any Israelite who happens to be present in the land. It misunderstands the Abrahamic covenant: the land promise was tied to the covenant relationship, not to physical occupation. The exilic situation had not been created by YHWH&rsquo;s weakness but by his covenant judgment.</p>",
    "25": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s threefold indictment of the land-remnant: (1) &ldquo;You eat flesh with the blood in it&rdquo; &mdash; violation of Gen 9:4 and Lev 17:14 (blood prohibition, the most basic food-purity law). (2) &ldquo;You lift your eyes to your idols&rdquo; (<em>giluleikem</em>) &mdash; the idolatry charge Ezekiel has leveled throughout the book. (3) &ldquo;You shed blood&rdquo; (<em>damim tishpeku</em>) &mdash; murder or judicial blood. The three charges span cultic purity, first-commandment faithfulness, and social justice. The rhetorical question &ldquo;do you expect to possess the land?&rdquo; destroys the remnant&rsquo;s Abrahamic argument by showing they do not meet the covenant conditions that made the Abrahamic promise possible.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&ldquo;You rely on your sword&rdquo; (<em>amadtem al-charbekem</em>) &mdash; military self-reliance in place of YHWH-trust, the characteristic failure of Judah&rsquo;s leadership that Ezekiel has condemned from the beginning (Ezek 17; 23). &ldquo;You commit abominations (<em>toevah</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; the comprehensive term for covenant violations. &ldquo;Each of you defiles his neighbor&rsquo;s wife&rdquo; &mdash; sexual immorality in addition to cultic and violent sins. The three charges of v. 26 parallel the three in v. 25, completing the indictment: those claiming the land by Abrahamic right are themselves living in violation of the covenant conditions that make the land-promise operational.</p>",
    "27": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s threefold judgment on the three groups in the land: &ldquo;those in the ruins will fall by the sword; those in the open field I will give to the beasts to be devoured; those in strongholds and caves will die by pestilence.&rdquo; The tripartite destruction echoes the covenant curse triad of sword, wild beast, and pestilence (&ldquo;my three disastrous acts of judgment,&rdquo; Ezek 14:21; from Lev 26:25-26). The judgment is geographically comprehensive &mdash; no physical location in the land provides safety for the covenant-breaking remnant. Geography cannot substitute for covenant faithfulness.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&ldquo;I will make the land a desolate waste (<em>shemmah umeshammah</em>), and her arrogant pride will cease&rdquo; &mdash; the complete desolation of the land is the covenant curse of Lev 26:31-35: &ldquo;I will make your cities a waste and will devastate your sanctuaries.&rdquo; The phrase &ldquo;arrogant pride&rdquo; (<em>gaon uzzah</em>) &mdash; the presumptuous national self-confidence of those claiming the land &mdash; is the same sin Ezekiel condemned in Jerusalem before its fall (7:24: &ldquo;the pride of the strong shall cease&rdquo;). The land desolation also fulfills Jer 25:11: &ldquo;this whole land shall become a ruin and a waste, and these nations shall serve the king of Babylon seventy years.&rdquo;</p>",
    "29": "<p>&ldquo;Then they will know that I am the LORD when I have made the land a desolate waste because of all the abominations they have committed.&rdquo; The recognition formula (<em>lema-an yed-u ki ani YHWH</em>) applied to judgment: the desolation itself becomes the vehicle for divine self-disclosure. The irony is pointed: the remnant who cited the Abrahamic promise (&ldquo;the land is ours&rdquo;) will learn YHWH&rsquo;s identity precisely through the forfeiture of that land. Knowledge of YHWH in Ezekiel is never merely propositional; it comes through experienced events of covenant judgment and restoration.</p>",
    "30": "<p>&ldquo;Your people are talking about you by the walls and at the doorways of houses&rdquo; &mdash; the social setting here is the exilic community in Babylonia, where Ezekiel lived among the Tel-abib community (3:15). The &ldquo;walls and doorways of houses&rdquo; are the informal gathering places of the Babylonian exile quarter. &ldquo;Come, let us hear what word is coming from the LORD&rdquo; &mdash; the phrase <em>yotzet min-YHWH</em> (going out from YHWH, the word coming from YHWH) treats Ezekiel&rsquo;s prophecies as interesting events to discuss, not directives to obey. The exilic community&rsquo;s attitude is one of curious spectatorship rather than responsive engagement.</p>",
    "31": "<p>&ldquo;They come to you as the people come, and they sit before you as my people and hear your words &mdash; but they will not act on them.&rdquo; The phrase &ldquo;as my people&rdquo; (<em>ka-am</em>) is pointed: they present themselves in the posture of covenant people but without the substance. &ldquo;With their mouths they express devotion (<em>agavim</em>) but their hearts pursue dishonest gain.&rdquo; <em>Agavim</em> (excessive love, passionate devotion) is a term associated with erotic longing (Jer 4:30; Ezek 23 passim) &mdash; here used ironically: their &ldquo;devotion&rdquo; to Ezekiel&rsquo;s words is as shallow as infatuation. &ldquo;Their hearts pursue dishonest gain (<em>bitztam libbam holech</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; the heart&rsquo;s actual orientation is commercial/acquisitive rather than covenantal.</p>",
    "32": "<p>&ldquo;You are to them like a love song sung by one with a beautiful voice and skilled on an instrument&rdquo; (<em>shir agavim</em>, a song of erotic longing) &mdash; the comparison is memorably deflating. The prophet who has been warning of YHWH&rsquo;s judgment, mourning Jerusalem&rsquo;s fall, and calling to repentance is being received as entertainment. The parallel in 1 Kgs 14:12 and Amos 6:5 presents musical performance as the self-indulgent activity of those who ignore coming judgment. &ldquo;They hear your words but will not act on them (<em>lo ya-asun</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; the gap between hearing and doing is the diagnostic of covenant nominal adherence (cf. Jas 1:22-23, which draws on this OT pattern).</p>",
    "33": "<p>&ldquo;But when it comes &mdash; and it will come (<em>ki hinneh baa uv-aa</em>) &mdash; then they will know that a prophet has been among them.&rdquo; The emphatic doubled verb <em>baa uv-aa</em> (literally: &lsquo;behold coming and it comes&rsquo;) &mdash; a Qal active participle followed by a perfect &mdash; expresses the absolute certainty of the coming fulfillment. The delayed recognition &mdash; knowing a prophet was among them only after the prophecy is fulfilled &mdash; echoes the self-vindicating prophecy principle of Deut 18:21-22. Ezekiel&rsquo;s audience will acknowledge his prophetic authenticity not through present responsiveness but through retrospective recognition when events demonstrate the accuracy of YHWH&rsquo;s word.</p>"
  },
  "34": {
    "1": "<p>The new oracular formula introduces ch. 34, which contains one of the most influential prophetic oracles in the OT: the shepherd discourse. The metaphor of ruler-as-shepherd was ubiquitous in ancient Near Eastern royal ideology. Hammurabi (18th c. BCE) called himself &ldquo;the shepherd of the black-headed people.&rdquo; Egyptian pharaohs carried the crook (<em>heqa</em>) as the shepherd&rsquo;s staff symbol of royal authority. The Sumerian concept of the king as shepherd (<em>sipa</em>) governed Mesopotamian royal self-presentation from at least the 3rd millennium BCE. Ezekiel mobilizes this common ANE metaphor to indict Israel&rsquo;s ruling class (kings, nobles, priests) for failure to perform their shepherding obligations.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&ldquo;Woe to the shepherds of Israel who feed themselves!&rdquo; &mdash; the indictment begins with the rhetorical <em>hoi</em> (woe) formula, typically used for funeral laments or prophetic condemnations (Isa 5:8-23; Ezek 13:3, 18). The shepherds feed (<em>ro-im</em>) themselves; the flock they do not feed. The Hebrew root <em>ra-ah</em> (to shepherd, to graze, to tend) is used for both the shepherds&rsquo; self-feeding and the failing of the flock &mdash; the same activity directed at themselves rather than at those entrusted to them. The oracle is addressed to the class of leaders responsible for Jerusalem&rsquo;s fall: kings (Jehoiakim, Jehoiachin, Zedekiah) and the ruling establishment.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The catalog of self-enrichment at the flock&rsquo;s expense: eating the fat (<em>helev</em>, the choicest portion), wearing the wool, slaughtering the fatlings &mdash; all the best products of the flock are consumed by the shepherd rather than used to care for the sheep. The fat, wool, and choice animals were the economically valuable outputs of the flock. The metaphor maps precisely onto the Jerusalem ruling class&rsquo;s extraction of resources from the population: the prophetic literature consistently condemns the wealthy&rsquo;s exploitation of the poor (Amos 2:6-8; Isa 3:14-15; Mic 3:1-3).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The fourfold failure of the shepherds stated as a comprehensive catalog of neglect: (1) &ldquo;You have not strengthened the weak (<em>lo chizzaqtem la-chalashim</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; the weak were left without reinforcement; (2) &ldquo;healed the sick (<em>lo refattem la-cholah</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; the diseased received no treatment; (3) &ldquo;bound up the injured (<em>la-nishberet lo chabashtem</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; the broken limb got no splinting; (4) &ldquo;brought back the strayed (<em>hanidachat lo hashevothem</em>) or sought the lost (<em>ha-avedat lo viqqashtem</em>).&rdquo; The catalog is a negative checklist of the ideal shepherd&rsquo;s duties &mdash; Jesus&rsquo;s self-description in John 10 and the Good Samaritan parable in Luke 10 are direct echoes of this passage&rsquo;s imagery. &ldquo;With force and harshness you have ruled them (<em>bechazaqah uvepharech reditem otam</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; <em>pharech</em> (harshness, cruelty) is the word used in Exod 1:13-14 for Egypt&rsquo;s ruthless treatment of Israel in slavery. The leaders have become Egypt to their own people.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;They were scattered because there was no shepherd (<em>ein ro-eh</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; the direct cause of Israel&rsquo;s dispersion is the absence of true leadership. The sheep &ldquo;became food for every wild beast&rdquo; (<em>la-achlah lekhol-chayat hassadeh</em>) &mdash; the predatory nations that devoured the leaderless population. The scattering (<em>vayyaputzu</em>) is both the geographic reality of the Babylonian dispersion and the theological consequence of covenant abandonment: YHWH had warned in the Deuteronomic curses that Israel would be scattered among the nations (Deut 28:64).</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;My sheep wandered over all the mountains and on every high hill&rdquo; &mdash; note the possessive: these are &ldquo;my sheep&rdquo; (<em>tzoni</em>, YHWH&rsquo;s flock). The contrast with the &ldquo;shepherds of Israel&rdquo; is deliberate: the human shepherds (Israel&rsquo;s kings) have failed YHWH&rsquo;s flock, not merely a human flock. The mountains and high hills are the geographic features of Canaan&rsquo;s landscape, evoking the widespread dispersion across the land before the final deportation. &ldquo;With no one to search or seek for them (<em>lo dorush velo mevaqqesh</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; the two verbs (<em>darash</em>, to inquire/seek diligently; <em>baqash</em>, to seek) mirror the verbs YHWH will use of himself in v. 11, creating the rhetorical contrast between the absent human shepherds and the seeking divine shepherd.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The legal summons formula: &ldquo;Therefore, you shepherds, hear the word of the LORD.&rdquo; The word <em>lachen</em> (therefore) introduces the consequential judgment following the indictment of vv. 2-6. The legal proceedings against the shepherds require a formal hearing formula to separate the accusation from the verdict. The formula &ldquo;hear the word of the LORD (<em>shim-u devar YHWH</em>)&rdquo; is used throughout the prophets to introduce covenantal pronouncements to specific audiences (Amos 5:1; Jer 2:4).</p>",
    "8": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s oath of indictment: &ldquo;As I live (<em>chai ani</em>), because my flock has become a prey and food for all the wild beasts, since there was no shepherd, and because my shepherds have not searched for my flock but have fed themselves rather than feeding my flock.&rdquo; The protracted subordinate clause &mdash; the &ldquo;because&rdquo; clause that fills the entire verse &mdash; makes the causal connection explicit: the predation of the flock is directly traceable to the shepherds&rsquo; self-service and failure to seek. The oath formula guarantees that the following verdict (v. 10) will be executed without qualification.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The second summons of the shepherds to hear the word of YHWH repeats v. 7 verbatim, creating the Hebrew rhetorical pattern of double announcement before a significant declaration. The repetition is not redundant but emphatic &mdash; the formal juridical structure of a legal proceeding requires that the accused be clearly addressed before the verdict is read. The shepherds are explicitly identified as the defendants in YHWH&rsquo;s court.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&ldquo;Behold I am against the shepherds (<em>hineni el-haro-im</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; the adversative formula <em>hineni el</em> (I am against) is Ezekiel&rsquo;s characteristic announcement of divine opposition to a specific entity (13:8; 21:8; 26:3; 28:22). &ldquo;I will hold them accountable for my flock (<em>uviqashti et-tzoni mi-yadam</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; the verb <em>baqash</em> (to seek, to require) used earlier for the shepherds&rsquo; failure to seek the scattered flock is now turned against the shepherds: YHWH will require (<em>baqash</em>) the flock from their hand. The juridical reversal is precise. &ldquo;I will rescue my flock from their mouths that it may not be food for them&rdquo; &mdash; the same &ldquo;food&rdquo; vocabulary (v. 5) is now applied to the shepherds themselves eating the sheep, not the wild beasts.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&ldquo;For thus says the Lord GOD: Behold, I myself will search for my sheep and seek them out (<em>vedarashti et-tzoni uveqartim</em>).&rdquo; The emphatic &ldquo;I myself (<em>ani</em>)&rdquo; marks the climactic shift from the failed human shepherds to the divine shepherd who personally takes up the task. The two verbs (<em>darash</em>, to search diligently; <em>baqar</em>, to seek/examine) are the mirror of the human shepherds&rsquo; failure in v. 6 (&ldquo;no one to search or seek&rdquo;). YHWH&rsquo;s personal assumption of the shepherding role is the radical claim of the passage: the divine king of Israel will do what Israel&rsquo;s human kings failed to do. John 10:11 (&ldquo;I am the good shepherd&rdquo;) is the NT&rsquo;s claim that Jesus is the enactment of this YHWH-as-shepherd promise in human form.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;As a shepherd seeks out his flock when some of his sheep have been scattered, so will I seek out my sheep.&rdquo; The simile draws on pastoral practice: the owner of a scattered flock personally combs the terrain to locate each missing animal. &ldquo;I will rescue them from all the places where they have been scattered on a day of clouds and thick darkness (<em>beyom anan va-arafel</em>).&rdquo; The phrase &ldquo;day of clouds and thick darkness&rdquo; is the vocabulary of theophany (Exod 19:9; Deut 4:11) and divine judgment (Joel 2:2; Zeph 1:15) &mdash; the gathering will happen precisely in the moment of historical catastrophe, not despite it but through it.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;I will bring them out from the peoples and gather them from the countries (<em>vegibbatstim min-ha-aratzot</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; the new exodus/restoration language that governs Ezekiel 33-48. The gathering of the dispersed (<em>qibbuts galuyot</em>, ingathering of exiles) is the prophetic program announced here and developed in chs. 36-37. &ldquo;I will bring them into their own land. I will feed them on the mountains of Israel, by the streams, and in all the inhabited places.&rdquo; The mountains of Israel &mdash; which in ch. 35 will be contrasted with Mount Seir&rsquo;s desolation &mdash; become the site of restoration pastoral abundance.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;I will feed them in good pasture, and their fold shall be on the mountain heights of Israel (<em>bemaromi Yisrael</em>).&rdquo; The mountain heights of Israel are the geographic inverse of the &ldquo;every high hill&rdquo; on which the sheep wandered leaderless in v. 6. The restoration involves returning to the same terrain, but under YHWH&rsquo;s direct shepherding rather than human negligence. &ldquo;On rich pasture (<em>mireh shamen</em>) they shall feed on the mountains of Israel.&rdquo; The restored covenant community will enjoy the actual material blessing of the promised land &mdash; the covenant promise of Deut 8:7-9 fulfilled after the judgment period.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;I myself will be the shepherd of my flock (<em>ani er-eh tzoni</em>), and I myself will make them lie down (<em>ani arbi-itsem</em>), declares the Lord GOD.&rdquo; The doubled <em>ani</em> (I myself) is emphatic repetition for rhetorical force: YHWH is not delegating the shepherding role but personally performing it. The phrase &ldquo;make them lie down&rdquo; (<em>arbi-itsem</em>) evokes Psalm 23:2 (&ldquo;He makes me lie down in green pastures&rdquo;) &mdash; Psalm 23 is the lyrical meditation on exactly this promise, where YHWH-as-shepherd performs each action that Israel&rsquo;s failed shepherds neglected. The oracle of ch. 34 is the juridical-prophetic prose behind the Psalm&rsquo;s poetic confessions.</p>",
    "16": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s shepherd duties as the positive fulfillment of the negative catalog of the human shepherds&rsquo; failures (v. 4): &ldquo;I will seek the lost, bring back the strayed, bind up the injured, and strengthen the weak.&rdquo; Each item directly reverses the failure-catalog. &ldquo;But the fat and the strong I will destroy (<em>ve-hashemen ve-hachazaq eshamed</em>); I will feed them in justice (<em>mishpat</em>).&rdquo; The intra-flock judgment &mdash; between those who exploited the weak and the vulnerable who were exploited &mdash; introduces the second movement of the chapter (vv. 17-22). YHWH&rsquo;s shepherding is not mere benevolence but includes active justice on behalf of the marginalized.</p>",
    "17": "<p>&ldquo;As for you, my flock, thus says the Lord GOD: Behold, I judge between sheep and sheep, between rams and male goats.&rdquo; The oracle extends beyond the external human shepherds to the internal dynamics of the community itself. The &ldquo;rams and male goats&rdquo; (<em>eilim u-attudim</em>) &mdash; the dominant animals within the flock &mdash; represent the powerful members of the covenant community who took advantage of their position. In pastoral practice, dominant rams push less dominant sheep away from water and pasture. The social-class application is clear: the wealthy and powerful within Israel exploited the weak and poor.</p>",
    "18": "<p>&ldquo;Is it not enough for you to feed on the good pasture, that you must tread down with your feet the rest of your pasture?&rdquo; The metaphor of fouling the water supply and trampling the pasture captures the social reality of elite economic behavior: not merely consuming the good, but actively destroying what others could have used. Muddy water and trampled pasture are useless to those who come after the dominant animals. The economic application: the wealthy not only monopolized resources but destroyed the productive capacity of the commons through their practices.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&ldquo;Must my flock eat what you have trodden with your feet, and drink what you have muddied with your feet?&rdquo; The rhetorical question completes the social-class analysis: the poor receive the remnants degraded by the rich &mdash; trampled food and fouled water. This imagery is the pastoral-allegorical expression of the prophetic social critique that runs from Amos through Isaiah through Jeremiah: the economic arrangements of pre-exile Israel systematically disadvantaged the poor while benefiting the rich. Ezekiel places the responsibility for this directly on the dominant members of the community.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&ldquo;Therefore, thus says the Lord GOD to them: Behold, I myself will judge between the fat sheep and the lean sheep.&rdquo; The <em>lachen</em> (therefore) introduces YHWH&rsquo;s personal judicial intervention in the intra-community social conflict. &ldquo;The fat sheep and the lean sheep&rdquo; (<em>bein seh briah lish-seh razah</em>) &mdash; fat (well-fed, economically privileged) versus lean (malnourished, economically marginalized). The divine judge takes the side of the lean sheep, not because they are morally superior, but because YHWH&rsquo;s covenant justice includes active vindication of the marginalized against those who exploited them.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&ldquo;Because you push with side and shoulder, and thrust at all the weak with your horns (<em>qarneikem tenachu</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; the physical behavior of dominant rams in a flock, used to describe the social aggression of the powerful members of the community. The horn (<em>qeren</em>) is the symbol of power throughout the OT (Ps 75:4-5; Dan 7:8; Amos 6:13). &ldquo;Until you have scattered them abroad (<em>pitzztam el-chutz</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; the rich have contributed to the scattering of the poor through economic predation, mirroring (and perhaps causing) the national scattering that YHWH judged.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&ldquo;I will rescue my flock, and they shall no longer be a prey (<em>levo-az liviz</em>).&rdquo; The promise of protection extends the shepherd imagery to its covenantal fullness: the restored community will not be subject to either external predators (other nations) or internal exploiters (the powerful within the community). &ldquo;I will judge between sheep and sheep&rdquo; &mdash; the repeated formula (first in v. 17, now in v. 22) closes the intra-community judgment section and introduces the Messianic promise of vv. 23-24. The establishment of justice within the community is the precondition for the appointment of the shepherd-king.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&ldquo;And I will set up over them one shepherd, my servant David (<em>eved david</em>), and he shall feed them.&rdquo; After the long account of YHWH&rsquo;s personal shepherding, this verse introduces the human agent through whom that shepherding will be exercised: &ldquo;my servant David.&rdquo; David had been dead for four centuries by Ezekiel&rsquo;s time; &ldquo;my servant David&rdquo; is therefore the Messianic figure who inherits David&rsquo;s royal office and covenant promises (2 Sam 7:12-16: &ldquo;I will raise up your offspring after you&rdquo;). The Davidic covenant is the framework: the one shepherd is not David personally but the Davidic heir who fulfils what David&rsquo;s dynasty was meant to be. Isaiah 11:1 (&ldquo;a shoot from the stump of Jesse&rdquo;), Jer 23:5 (&ldquo;a righteous Branch for David&rdquo;), and Zech 3:8; 6:12 (&ldquo;my servant the Branch&rdquo;) all operate within this same Davidic-Messianic promise framework.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&ldquo;And I, the LORD, will be their God, and my servant David shall be <em>nasi</em> (prince, leader) among them.&rdquo; The term <em>nasi</em> (prince, leader, elevated one) is Ezekiel&rsquo;s preferred title for the Messianic ruler rather than <em>melech</em> (king) &mdash; Ezekiel uses <em>nasi</em> for the restored Davidic leader throughout the temple vision (44:3; 45:7-17; 46:2-18; 48:21-22). The distinction may reflect a deliberate distancing from the failed <em>melech</em>-ship of Judah&rsquo;s kings: the restored leader will be a <em>nasi</em> under YHWH&rsquo;s kingship rather than an autonomous <em>melech</em>. The covenant formula &ldquo;I will be their God&rdquo; (<em>ani YHWH eloheichem</em>) closes the verse with the relational core of all the promises.</p>",
    "25": "<p>&ldquo;I will make a covenant of peace (<em>berit shalom</em>) with them.&rdquo; The covenant of peace appears in Ezekiel at 34:25 and 37:26 and in Isaiah at 54:10 and 66:12 &mdash; it is the eschatological covenant that fulfills and exceeds the Mosaic covenant. The <em>berit shalom</em> (covenant of peace/completeness/well-being) uses <em>shalom</em> in its full sense of total well-being, not merely the absence of conflict. &ldquo;Banish wild beasts from the land (<em>vehishhbati chayah ra-ah min-ha-aretz</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; wild animals as a covenant-curse symbol (Lev 26:22: &ldquo;I will send wild beasts against you&rdquo;; Ezek 14:15) are now removed as a covenant-blessing sign. The wilderness becomes safe, the forest navigable.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&ldquo;I will make them and the places around my hill a blessing (<em>berachah</em>), and I will send down the showers in their season (<em>geshem bito</em>).&rdquo; The seasonal rains are the most fundamental blessing in Palestine&rsquo;s agricultural calendar: the early rains (October-November) for planting and the latter rains (March-April) for grain. Their regularity was the covenant blessing of Deut 11:14 (&ldquo;I will give the rain of your land in its season&rdquo;) and their withholding the curse (Deut 28:24; 1 Kings 17&rsquo;s drought under Ahab). &ldquo;Showers of blessing (<em>gishme berachah yihyu</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; the phrase is deliberately comprehensive: the rain itself is theologically characterized as blessing, not merely as meteorological fact.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&ldquo;The trees of the field shall yield their fruit, and the earth shall yield its increase.&rdquo; The restored land&rsquo;s agricultural productivity is the material expression of covenant restoration (Lev 26:4: &ldquo;the land shall yield its increase and the trees of the field shall yield their fruit&rdquo;). &ldquo;They shall be secure in their land. And they shall know that I am the LORD, when I break the bars of their yoke (<em>beshivri et-motot ullam</em>).&rdquo; The &ldquo;bars of the yoke&rdquo; is the standard ANE metaphor for political subjugation under a foreign power (Jer 27:2-12: the yoke of Babylon). Breaking the yoke = release from political servitude = recognition of YHWH as the one who acts in history to liberate his people.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&ldquo;They shall no longer be a prey to the nations, nor shall the beasts of the land devour them.&rdquo; The double security from both political (nations) and natural (wild beasts) threats completes the reversal of the covenant curses (Lev 26:22, 25). &ldquo;They shall dwell securely (<em>lavetech</em>) and none shall make them afraid (<em>ein machared</em>).&rdquo; The phrase <em>lavetech... ein machared</em> is the formula of covenant security that appears in Lev 26:6 and throughout the prophetic restoration oracles (Jer 23:6; 33:16; Mic 4:4; Zeph 3:13). Security from fear is the fundamental experiential quality of restored covenant life.</p>",
    "29": "<p>&ldquo;And I will provide for them a renowned planting (<em>matta leshemah</em>), so that they shall no more be consumed with famine in the land.&rdquo; <em>Matta leshemah</em> (a planting for/of reputation, a renowned plantation) &mdash; the phrase is unique to Ezekiel and difficult. It likely refers to an established, productive agricultural community whose abundance is recognized by surrounding nations (&ldquo;renowned&rdquo; in the sense of known for its fruitfulness). &ldquo;No longer suffer the disgrace of the nations (<em>lo yis-u od cherpat hagoyim</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; the shame of exile and dispossession has been the national disgrace; the restoration removes it. Honor-shame was not merely an emotional category in ancient Israel but a social reality with economic and political dimensions.</p>",
    "30": "<p>&ldquo;They shall know that I, the LORD their God, am with them (<em>otam</em>), and that they, the house of Israel, are my people (<em>ami</em>), declares the Lord GOD.&rdquo; The mutual covenant formula (&ldquo;I am their God / they are my people&rdquo;) is the relational core of all the preceding material restoration (land, rain, security, food). It is the Sinai covenant formula (Exod 6:7; Lev 26:12) given its eschatological fullness: the mechanical national covenant becomes a known relational reality. The NT fulfillment is the Incarnation and Pentecost: Emmanuel (God-with-us) and the Spirit&rsquo;s indwelling are the &ldquo;I am with them&rdquo; realized in person and power.</p>",
    "31": "<p>&ldquo;You are my sheep, human sheep of my pasture (<em>tzon mar-iti tzon adam atten</em>), and I am your God, declares the Lord GOD.&rdquo; The closing verse&rsquo;s phrase <em>tzon adam</em> (human sheep, literally &ldquo;sheep of humans / humankind&rdquo;) may be distinguishing Israel from literal sheep while maintaining the metaphor, or emphasizing the personal relational ownership: human beings who are YHWH&rsquo;s flock, not merely livestock. The closing covenant declaration &ldquo;I am your God&rdquo; in the mouth of YHWH directly echoes &ldquo;I am the LORD your God&rdquo; from the Decalogue (Exod 20:2) &mdash; the shepherd oracle ends where the covenant began: with YHWH&rsquo;s self-identifying declaration of covenant ownership.</p>"
  },
  "35": {
    "1": "<p>The oracular formula introduces ch. 35, an oracle against Mount Seir (= Edom). Its placement between the shepherd oracle of ch. 34 and the restoration oracle for Israel&rsquo;s mountains in ch. 36 is structurally significant: Edom&rsquo;s desolation and Israel&rsquo;s restoration are the two sides of the same divine act. Ch. 35&rsquo;s desolation of Mount Seir (vv. 3, 4, 7, 9) provides the dark foil for ch. 36&rsquo;s promise to Israel&rsquo;s mountains.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&ldquo;Son of man, set your face toward Mount Seir and prophesy against it (<em>hinnavei alav</em>).&rdquo; Mount Seir (the mountainous region of Edom, southeast of the Dead Sea, modern Jordan) is identified in Genesis with Esau and his descendants (Gen 36:8: &ldquo;Esau settled in the hill country of Seir; Esau is Edom&rdquo;). The Jacob-Esau conflict that began in the womb (Gen 25:22-23) and continued through the sale of the birthright (Gen 25:29-34) and the stolen blessing (Gen 27) is the ancestral backstory for the prophetic enmity between Israel and Edom. The directional command &ldquo;set your face toward&rdquo; is Ezekiel&rsquo;s standard prophetic-confrontation posture (6:2; 13:17; 25:2).</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;Behold, I am against you, Mount Seir (<em>hineni eleicha har seir</em>).&rdquo; The adversative formula <em>hineni el</em> (I am against you) that Ezekiel uses for the most severe divine declarations of hostility (against the false prophets, 13:8; against the nations, 26:3; 28:22; 29:3). The promise to &ldquo;stretch out my hand against you (<em>venatateti yadei aleicha</em>)&rdquo; uses the standard ANE gesture of divine power-in-action (the &ldquo;outstretched arm&rdquo; of divine agency, cf. Exod 3:20; 6:6; Deut 4:34). &ldquo;A desolation and a waste (<em>shemmah umeshammah</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; the identical double formula used for the land of Israel in 33:28, now directed at Edom.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;Your cities I will lay waste (<em>arev arev</em>), and you shall become a desolation.&rdquo; The judgment of Edom&rsquo;s cities fulfills the earlier oracle against Edom in Ezek 25:12-14 and the entire book of Obadiah. The recognition formula &ldquo;you shall know that I am the LORD&rdquo; is used here for an enemy nation: YHWH&rsquo;s identity is disclosed to Edom through judgment, not salvation. The same recognition formula that in chs. 33-37 prompts Israel&rsquo;s restoration produces a different recognition in Edom: acknowledgment of YHWH&rsquo;s power over their destruction.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;Because you cherished perpetual enmity (<em>eivat olam</em>) and gave over the people of Israel to the power of the sword (<em>higarta livnei Yisrael al-yadei charev</em>).&rdquo; <em>Eivat olam</em> (perpetual enmity, literally &ldquo;enmity of eternity/long-standing enmity&rdquo;) is the causal charge. The Edom-Israel hostility had deep historical roots in the Exodus period: Edom refused Israel passage through their territory (Num 20:14-21) and Saul&rsquo;s wars with Edom (1 Sam 14:47). &ldquo;At the time of their calamity, at the time of their final punishment (<em>beet eidam beet avon kets</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; the specific accusation: Edom exploited Israel&rsquo;s moment of greatest weakness (the 586 BCE Babylonian conquest) to join in the slaughter. Obadiah 10-14 is the most detailed account of Edom&rsquo;s specific crimes during Jerusalem&rsquo;s fall: standing aloof, rejoicing, looting, cutting off fugitives.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;As I live, declares the Lord GOD, I will destine you for blood (<em>ledamim essa-cha</em>), and blood shall pursue you (<em>vedamim yirdephucha</em>).&rdquo; The talion principle in covenantal form: Edom handed Israel over to the sword; YHWH will make Edom the target of blood-guilt. &ldquo;Since you did not hate bloodshed (<em>vedamim lo sane-ta</em>), bloodshed shall pursue you.&rdquo; The moral logic of covenantal retribution: what a nation welcomes as a tool against others, they receive in return. The phrase &ldquo;bloodshed shall pursue you&rdquo; uses the image of blood-guilt as an active pursuer &mdash; blood-guilt was in ancient Israelite legal thought a kind of supernatural force that demanded satisfaction (Gen 4:10: &ldquo;your brother&rsquo;s blood cries to me from the ground&rdquo;).</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;I will make Mount Seir a waste and a desolation, and I will cut off from it all who come and go (<em>veechrat mimenu over vashaV</em>).&rdquo; The phrase &ldquo;cut off all who come and go&rdquo; describes the complete end of normal human habitation and travel &mdash; the paths and routes through Edom&rsquo;s territory will be abandoned. Edom&rsquo;s strategic position astride the King&rsquo;s Highway (the major north-south trade route along the Transjordanian plateau) made it a commercially important territory; cutting off traffic through it removes both the people and their economic function.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&ldquo;I will fill its mountains with the slain (<em>uchaleti et-hareicha chalalim</em>).&rdquo; The use of <em>harim</em> (mountains) for Edom&rsquo;s terrain specifically anticipates the contrast with the &ldquo;mountains of Israel&rdquo; in ch. 36 &mdash; Edom&rsquo;s mountains will be filled with the slain while Israel&rsquo;s mountains will be filled with the returned people. &ldquo;On your hills and in your valleys and in all your ravines those slain by the sword shall fall&rdquo; &mdash; the comprehensive geographic formula (&ldquo;hills, valleys, ravines&rdquo;) emphasizes that no terrain feature of Edom escapes. The same geographic comprehensiveness applied to Israel&rsquo;s restoration in 36:4 (&ldquo;to the mountains and hills, the ravines and valleys&rdquo;).</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;I will make you a perpetual desolation (<em>shemamot olam</em>), and your cities shall not return to be inhabited.&rdquo; <em>Shemamot olam</em> (perpetual/eternal desolation) is the strongest possible desolation language &mdash; it contrasts with Edom&rsquo;s hope of possessing Israel&rsquo;s land permanently (v. 10). The historical record: the Nabataean Arab kingdom that occupied Edom&rsquo;s territory from the 4th century BCE effectively displaced the Edomite population. By the NT period, Idumea (the Hellenistic name for Edom) had been largely absorbed into Judea under John Hyrcanus (125 BCE), and the Edomite population as a distinct entity disappeared. The desolation oracle found its historical fulfillment in stages. The recognition formula closes the verse.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&ldquo;Because you said, &lsquo;These two nations and these two countries shall be mine, and we will possess them&rsquo; &mdash; although the LORD was there (<em>va-YHWH sham hayah</em>).&rdquo; The two nations and two countries are Israel and Judah (or the northern and southern kingdoms). Edom&rsquo;s territorial ambition at the moment of Israel&rsquo;s collapse (586 BCE) is the second charge, supplementing the blood-guilt of v. 5. &ldquo;Although the LORD was there&rdquo; is the pregnant parenthetical that undermines Edom&rsquo;s possession claim: Edom apparently concluded that YHWH had abandoned the land when Israel was defeated. But Ezekiel consistently insists that YHWH&rsquo;s departure from the temple (chs. 10-11) was a temporary covenant judgment, not a permanent abandonment. YHWH&rsquo;s presence in the land makes the land untransferable to another people.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&ldquo;As I live, declares the Lord GOD, I will deal with you according to the anger and envy that you showed through your hatred of them.&rdquo; The lex talionis applied at the emotional-motivational level: Edom&rsquo;s anger and envy against Israel become the measure of YHWH&rsquo;s response against Edom. &ldquo;I will make myself known among them when I judge you (<em>venodati vahem beshofteki otach</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; YHWH&rsquo;s self-revelation through the judgment of Edom is for the benefit of Israel: Israel will see and know YHWH through his vindication of them against their ancient enemy. Divine judgment of enemies is, in the covenantal framework, simultaneously defense of the victim.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;And you shall know that I am the LORD. I have heard all the insults (<em>neatzu-teicha</em>) you hurled against the mountains of Israel, saying, &lsquo;They are laid desolate; they are given to us to devour.&rsquo;&rdquo; The &ldquo;mountains of Israel&rdquo; that Edom gloated over in desolation are the very mountains that will be addressed in YHWH&rsquo;s restoration oracle of ch. 36. Edom&rsquo;s speech against the mountains of Israel (&ldquo;they are ours to devour&rdquo;) is the direct foil for YHWH&rsquo;s speech to the mountains of Israel (&ldquo;I will restore you&rdquo;, 36:1-15). The insults (<em>neatzu</em>) have been heard &mdash; prophetic oracles against Edom appear in Isa 34; Jer 49:7-22; Amos 1:11-12; Obadiah; Mal 1:2-5.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;And you spoke arrogantly against me with your mouth and multiplied your words against me; I heard it.&rdquo; Edom&rsquo;s insults against Israel&rsquo;s mountains (v. 12) are simultaneously insults against YHWH: since YHWH is identified with the land and people of Israel, contempt for Israel&rsquo;s desolation is contempt for YHWH&rsquo;s apparent defeat. The phrase &ldquo;multiplied your words against me (<em>higgadetm alay pi-chem)</em>&rdquo; escalates from insults to arrogant boasting against the divine sovereign. &ldquo;I heard it (<em>ani shamati</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; the divine hearing of defiant speech is consistently the trigger for prophetic judgment in the OT (Ps 94:7-11; Isa 37:28-29; Ezek 25:3, 8, 12).</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;Thus says the Lord GOD: While the whole earth rejoices (<em>besimchath kol-ha-aretz</em>), I will make you a desolation.&rdquo; The cosmic reversal: at the moment of Edom&rsquo;s desolation, the entire earth celebrates. The phrase &ldquo;the whole earth rejoices&rdquo; anticipates the restoration of Israel and the nations&rsquo; response to it (cf. Ps 96:11-12; Isa 44:23; 49:13). Edom&rsquo;s desolation is not a private event but a cosmic moment in which YHWH&rsquo;s justice is publicly displayed. The contrast with Edom&rsquo;s rejoicing over Israel&rsquo;s desolation (v. 15) completes the reversal: what Edom did to Israel, YHWH does to Edom, while all the earth watches.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;As you rejoiced over the inheritance of the house of Israel because it was desolate, so I will deal with you. You shall be desolate, Mount Seir, and all Edom, all of it.&rdquo; The precise lex talionis closure: the proportionality of Edom&rsquo;s desolation to their rejoicing over Israel&rsquo;s desolation. &ldquo;Then they shall know that I am the LORD.&rdquo; The recognition formula closes the oracle as it has closed the other judgment oracles throughout Ezekiel. In the structure of chs. 35-36, Edom learns YHWH&rsquo;s identity through their judgment (35:15), while Israel learns YHWH&rsquo;s identity through their restoration (36:11) &mdash; two modes of the same divine self-disclosure that constitutes the theological purpose of the entire historical movement.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'ezekiel')
    merge_comm(existing, EZEKIEL)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'ezekiel', existing)
    print('Ezekiel 33-35 mkt-context written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
